{{Infobox artist | name = Jenaro Pérez Villaamil | image = Jenaro Pérez Villaamil.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Portrait of Jenaro Pérez Villaamil by unknown artist, 1843 | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = | birth_date = 3 February 1807 | birth_place = [[Ferrol, Galicia]], Spain | death_date = 5 June 1854 | death_place = Madrid, Spain | resting_place = | nationality = Spanish | residence = | education = [[Santiago de Compostela]] | alma_mater = | known_for = Painter | notable_works = | style = | movement = [[Orientalism|Orientalist]]; [[Romanticism|Romantic]] | spouse = | partner = | awards = | elected = | patrons = | memorials = | website = | module = }}
'''Jenaro Pérez de Villaamil y d'Huguet''' (3 February 1807 &ndash; 5 June 1854) was a [[Spanish people|Spanish]] painter in the [[Romanticism|Romantic]] style who specialized in landscapes with figures and architectural scenes. He often inflated the scale of the buildings relative to the figures to make them more impressive.
== Biography == He was born in [[Ferrol, Galicia]]. In 1812, he was enrolled at the military academy in [[Santiago de Compostela]], where he assisted his father, who was a professor there.<ref name="A">[http://www.arteespana.com/genaroperezvillaamil.htm Briuef biography and works] @ Arte España.</ref> He went to Madrid in 1820 to study at the "Reales Estudios de San Isidro" (now part of the [[Colegio Imperial de Madrid]]). Three years later, he went to [[Cádiz]] to enlist in the army fighting the "[[Hundred Thousand Sons of Saint Louis]]" sent by the [[Louis Antoine, Duke of Angoulême|Duke of Angoulême]]. He was wounded and briefly held as a prisoner of war.<ref name="P">[http://www.museodelprado.es/enciclopedia/enciclopedia-on-line/voz/perez-villaamil-y-duguet-jenaro/ Brief biography] @ the [[Museo del Prado]] website.</ref> Afterwards, he remained there to study at the "Escuela de Bellas Artes".
In 1830, he went to [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], with his brother Juan (died 1863), who was also a painter, where they decorated the [[Teatro Tapia]] and remained there for a few more years, working as [[scenographer]]s.<ref name="M">[http://www.mcnbiografias.com/app-bio/do/show?key=perez-villaamil-jenaro Biography] @ MCN Biografías.</ref> Upon his return to Spain in 1833, he made the acquaintance of the Scottish painter [[David Roberts (painter)|David Roberts]],<ref name="P" /> who had a decisive influence on his style. He settled in Madrid in 1834 and became a member of the [[Real Academia de Bellas Artes de San Fernando]] the following year. In 1840, he was named honorary [[court painter]] to Queen [[Isabella II of Spain|Isabella II]]. During the regime of [[Baldomero Espartero]], from 1840 to 1844, he left his wife and young child and lived in self-imposed exile in France and Belgium, using artistic affairs as an excuse for his absence.<ref name="M" /> After travelling through Europe, he returned in 1845 and obtained the chair of landscape painting at the Academia, where he later became the director.<ref name="A" />
He returned to Galicia for an extended stay in 1849 and made extensive travels throughout Spain until 1852, when he began to suffer from liver disease.<ref name="A" /> He died in Madrid two years later, aged only forty-seven.
